    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: Federal tests of imported aerosol cosmetics have found 43 percent of them to contain chlorofluorocarbons, in violation of United States law, the Customs Service said today.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: Federal tests of imported aerosol cosmetics have found 43 percent of them to contain chlorofluorocarbons, in violation of United States law, the Customs Service said today.</p>
        <p>Federal tests of imported aerosol cosmetics have found 43 percent of them to contain chlorofluorocarbons, in violation of United States law, the Customs Service said today.</p>
        <p>The United States has banned most uses in aerosols of chlorofluorocarbons, which have been linked to destruction of the Earth's protective ozone layer.</p>
        <p>The samples represent at least 50 different brands of aerosol cosmetics, mostly perfumes made in France.</p>
        <p>The Government said it believed that many of the products were originally intended for sale on cruise ships or in countries that allow them.</p>
      </block>
